sections.english:
On one occasion, Venerable Sāriputta was dwelling in Sāvatthī, in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery. At that time, Venerable Sāriputta was instructing, urging, inspiring, and gladdening the bhikkhus with a Dhamma talk, using clear and articulate speech, free from stammering, and conveying the meaning effectively. And those bhikkhus, paying earnest attention, bearing it in mind, applying their whole mind, and lending an ear, listened to the Dhamma. Then it occurred to Venerable Vaṅgīsa: "Venerable Sāriputta is indeed instructing, urging, inspiring, and gladdening the bhikkhus with a Dhamma talk, using clear and articulate speech, free from stammering, and conveying the meaning effectively. And those bhikkhus, paying earnest attention, bearing it in mind, applying their whole mind, and lending an ear, listen to the Dhamma. Why don't I praise Venerable Sāriputta directly with appropriate verses?" Then Venerable Vaṅgīsa rose from his seat, arranged his upper robe over one shoulder, reverently saluted Venerable Sāriputta with clasped hands, and said to him: "It inspires me, friend Sāriputta! It inspires me, friend Sāriputta!" "Be inspired, friend Vaṅgīsa!" Then Venerable Vaṅgīsa praised Venerable Sāriputta directly with appropriate verses:

Of deep wisdom, intelligent, skilled in the path and not-path;
Sāriputta, the greatly wise, teaches the Dhamma to the bhikkhus.

He teaches concisely, and speaks expansively as well;
His inspired utterance resounds like the voice of a mynah bird.

As he teaches thus, they listen to his sweet voice;
With a voice that enchants, is pleasing to hear, and beautiful;
With uplifted and joyful hearts, the bhikkhus lend their ear.
